# Agent prompts and the autonomous evolution loop

This folder holds the prompts that drive Claude agents working on this project, plus the report directory for the autonomous loop. Two invocation modes share a common implementation core:

- **Autonomous mode** — fired on a schedule (cron, [`/loop`](https://docs.claude.com/en/docs/claude-code/slash-commands), or [`/schedule`](https://docs.claude.com/en/docs/claude-code/slash-commands)). Reads the roadmap, picks one queued improvement, implements it, commits to a worktree branch, and writes a one-screen report for the human.
- **Parent-driven mode** — fired by a parent Claude session via the Agent tool. The parent picks the IMP and hands the id to the sub-agent; the sub-agent does the implementation discipline and returns a structured report in chat for the parent to act on (typically a `--no-ff` merge).

Both modes share the same hard constraints: **never** commit to `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`, **never** push, **never** run if preconditions don't hold, never start a second IMP per invocation. Every run is independent and lives in its own git worktree.

## File layout

| File | Role |
|---|---|
| [`core.md`](./core.md) | **Shared implementation steps.** Read context → walk rubric (planning) → flip IMP status → implement → walk rubric (verification) + run `{{TYPE_CHECK_CMD}}` / `{{LINT_CMD}}` / `{{BUILD_CMD}}` → document (CHANGELOG, ADR, KP, IMP→done) → commit. Both wrappers below delegate to this file for the actual work. |
| [`prompt.md`](./prompt.md) | **Autonomous wrapper.** Adds: pre-flight initialization gate, IMP picking from the queue (with priority rules and "no eligible IMP, propose one" fallback), two-mode worktree setup (Mode A: from `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`; Mode B: harness-managed), in-flight status file in `reports/`, on-disk final report. |
| [`sub-agent-prompt.md`](./sub-agent-prompt.md) | **Parent-driven wrapper.** Adds: parameter section the parent fills (IMP id), pre-flight that *verifies* the parent's setup rather than creating it, structured prose report back to the parent in chat (no on-disk file). |
| [`reports/`](./reports/) | Per-run reports from the **autonomous** loop only. While a run is in flight the file is `<TS>.in-progress.md`; at the end the agent renames it to `<TS>.md`. The filename suffix is the terminal-state signal — `.in-progress.md` = running (or wedged); `.md` = over. Parent-driven runs **do not write here** — their output is the chat reply to the parent. |

The wrapper-core split is captured in [ADR-{{ADR_NUMBER_CORE}}](../decisions/{{ADR_NUMBER_CORE}}-shared-core-for-agent-prompts.md).

## How it works (autonomous mode)

```
cron (or /loop) ──▶  fires the agent
                          │
                          ▼
                  reads prompt.md
                          │
                          ▼
            pre-flight: check init gate (G1..G7)
                          │
                ┌─────────┴──────────┐
                │                    │
              FAIL                 PASS
                │                    │
                ▼                    ▼
          write FB-NNN          set up worktree (dual-mode):
          and STOP                Mode A — current branch is {{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}:
                                    create `../<repo>_autorun_<UTC>`
                                    on branch `autorun/<UTC>`
                                  Mode B — already on non-default branch
                                    (harness-managed worktree):
                                    use the current worktree
                                     │
                                     ▼
                          open reports/<UTC>.in-progress.md
                          (live status file; appended at each step)
                                     │
                                     ▼
                          pick ONE IMP-NNN by priority
                          (recorded in status file's Picked: header)
                                     │
                                     ▼
                          read core.md — follow Steps A–F
                          (with status-file appends at each named boundary)
                                     │
                                     ▼
                          append final report body, then
                          rename in-progress.md → reports/<UTC>.md
                                     │
                                     ▼
                          STOP. Worktree left for human review.
```

## Invocation options

### Autonomous mode — three ways to fire it

#### Option 1 — `claude` CLI in cron (most direct)

If you have the Claude Code CLI installed:

```cron
# Daily at 09:00 local time
0 9 * * * cd {{PROJECT_ROOT}} && claude -p "$(cat docs/autorun/prompt.md)" --dangerously-skip-permissions >> ~/{{PROJECT_NAME}}_autorun.log 2>&1
```

Or use the wrapper script: `scripts/autorun.sh`.

Notes:
- `cd` first so relative paths in the prompt resolve correctly.
- `--dangerously-skip-permissions` is required for non-interactive runs since the agent needs to edit files and run shell commands without an approval prompt. The autorun prompt enforces its own safety boundaries (no default-branch commits, no pushes, sandboxed worktree).

#### Option 2 — Claude Code `/loop`

```
/loop 24h docs/autorun/prompt.md
```

Stop with `/loop stop`.

#### Option 3 — Anthropic-hosted scheduled remote agents (`/schedule`)

```
/schedule
```

Then provide the prompt content.

### Parent-driven mode — Agent tool from inside a Claude session

When a parent Claude session is working on this project and wants to delegate one IMP to a sub-agent (e.g. to parallelize two independent IMPs in worktrees), it invokes the `Agent` tool with `isolation: "worktree"` and a prompt that points at [`sub-agent-prompt.md`](./sub-agent-prompt.md):

```
Agent({
  description: "Implement IMP-NNN",
  isolation: "worktree",
  prompt: `You are implementing one IMP for the {{PROJECT_NAME}} project.
Read {{PROJECT_ROOT}}/docs/autorun/sub-agent-prompt.md in full and follow it.

Your parameters:
- IMP to implement: IMP-NNN

Begin.`
})
```

The sub-agent runs in an isolated git worktree, follows [`core.md`](./core.md) for the implementation steps, commits on its worktree branch, and returns a structured prose report. The parent then merges with `--no-ff` (or discards). No file is written to `reports/` — the chat report is the handoff surface.

For parallel IMPs, the parent fires multiple `Agent` calls in a single message; they run concurrently in separate worktrees. The parent serially merges, resolving any conflicts (typically in `CHANGELOG.md` and `docs/backlog/improvements.md`).

## Reviewing what the agent did (autonomous mode)

After each run:

1. Open the latest report: `ls -t docs/autorun/reports/ | head -1`. Read it.
2. The report includes the worktree's absolute path.
3. Diff against `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`:
   ```bash
   cd ../<repo>_autorun_<timestamp>
   git diff {{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}..HEAD
   ```
4. If you like the work: merge it into `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}` (`git merge <branch> --no-ff` from the project root, NOT the worktree).
5. If you don't like it: delete the worktree (`git worktree remove ../<repo>_autorun_<timestamp> --force`).

### Mid-run observability

While a run is in progress, you can `ls docs/autorun/reports/` at any time to see what's happening:

- A `<TS>.in-progress.md` file means a run is currently going. Open it to see the timestamped step log.
- A `<TS>.md` file means the run finished (success, blocker, or proposal-only — the report's `Status:` line says which).
- A `<TS>.in-progress.md` file from a timestamp older than ~10 minutes is a **wedged run**: the agent hung before reaching the rename step. Investigate the worktree directly. The agent does not auto-rename on wedge so this signal is unambiguous.

## What the agent will NOT do

These are hard constraints encoded in `prompt.md` / `sub-agent-prompt.md` / `core.md`:

- Commit directly to `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`
- Push to a remote (regardless of whether one is configured)
- Modify `ROADMAP.md` strategic decisions D1–DN
- Touch files outside the chosen IMP's scope
- Skip the rubric walk
- Continue if `{{TYPE_CHECK_CMD}}` / `{{LINT_CMD}}` / `{{BUILD_CMD}}` fails
- Run if the initialization gate isn't satisfied (autonomous mode)
- Implement an item that's tagged for a future phase

## When the agent has nothing to do (autonomous mode)

If no `accepted` or `scheduled-phase-N` improvements exist for the current phase, the agent will:

1. Generate **one** new `IMP-NNN` proposal based on recent CHANGELOG gaps, open feedback, or current-phase deliverables that haven't been started.
2. Append it to `docs/backlog/improvements.md` with status `proposed`.
3. Stop without implementing it. Implementation only happens after the human reviews and bumps status to `accepted`.

This keeps the queue alive without letting the agent drift off-roadmap.

